'''Robert Peter Tabo Gale''' (born 3 August 1977) is an English-Canadian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] and current head coach of [[Valour FC]] in the [[Canadian Premier League]].

As a player, Gale began his career in England with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] before taking a break to focus on his coaching qualifications. He later appeared for Canadian clubs [[Winnipeg Alliance FC|Winnipeg Alliance]], [[Winnipeg Lucania FC|Winnipeg Lucania]] and [[FC Winnipeg Lions|Sons of Italy]]. Gale has also coached the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canadian national team]] from Under-16 to [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Under-20]], and became the first head coach and general manager of Valour FC in June 2018.

== Playing career ==
Gale was signed by [[Football League Third Division]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] as an associate schoolboy aged 14.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://valourfc.canpl.ca/article/rob-gale-named-inaugural-head-coach-gm|title=Rob Gale named inaugural Head Coach & GM|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=26 June 2018|work=Valour Football Club|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> After moving to [[Bedfordshire]] to study at university, he trained with [[Football League Second Division]] side [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] for a year.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://valourfc.canpl.ca/article/meet-the-coach-rob-gale|title=Meet the Coach: Rob Gale|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=26 June 2018|website=valourfc.canpl.ca|publisher=Valour Football Club|language=en-CA|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref>

After injury ruled Gale out for a full season and he graduated from university, he turned his attention to coaching and earned qualifications in [[England]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=":1" /> In 2001, upon moving to [[Canada]], Gale resumed his playing career and was named captained of indoor professional club the [[Winnipeg Alliance FC|Winnipeg Alliance]]. He later played for [[Winnipeg Lucania FC|Winnipeg Lucania]] and the [[FC Winnipeg Lions|Sons of Italy]] before retiring in 2012.<ref name=":0" />

== Coaching career ==

=== Early career ===
Initially working as a director for summer camps across the United States and the [[Ian Rush]] Finishing Schools, Gale became the director of soccer at [[Spencer High School and Auditorium|Spencer High School]] in Iowa in 2001. After two years, he became director for a North American academy run by [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], and later became the Canadian national director for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]'s sports academy.

=== Canada Soccer ===
In 2006, Gale was named technical director for the [[Manitoba Soccer Association]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/in-focus-robert-gale-p155998|title=In Focus: Robert Gale|last=|first=|date=2 March 2014|website=www.canadasoccer.com|publisher=Canada Soccer|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> In 2010, he became assistant coach for the [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17 men's national team]] and saw the team qualify for successive [[FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA Under-17 World Cup]] tournaments.<ref name=":3" /> In 2011, he came up against brother-in-law [[John Peacock (footballer)|John Peacock]], who was managing the [[England national under-17 football team|England U17 national team]].<ref name=":2" /> Later that year, he was named head coach for the Canada U16 men's national team, and in 2012 and became head coach of the [[Canada men's national under-18 soccer team|Canada U18 men's national team]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/?pid=1231&t=profile&|title=Rob Gale|last=|first=|date=14 July 2017|website=canadasoccer.com|publisher=Canada Soccer|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref>

In March 2014, Gale took over as the head coach of the [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Canada U20 men's national team]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/rob-gale-appointed-canada-s-men-s-u-20-team-head-coach-p156145|title=Rob Gale appointed Canada’s Men’s U-20 Team Head Coach|last=|first=|date=31 March 2014|work=Canada Soccer|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref>

=== Valour FC ===
On 26 June 2018, Gale was announced as the first head coach and general manager of [[Canadian Premier League]] club [[Valour FC]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/rob-gale-named-first-coach-and-gm-of-valour-fc-winnipeg-s-new-cpl-entry-1.23348630|title=Rob Gale named first coach and GM of Valour FC, Winnipeg's new CPL entry|last=Davidson|first=Neil|date=26 June 2018|work=Times Colonist|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Gale was born in [[Zambia]] to English parents while his father was working as a football coach. He also spent part of his childhood growing up in [[Tanzania]] before moving to England aged five.<ref name=":1" /> Living in [[Horley]], [[Surrey]], he attended [[Oakwood School, Horley|Oakwood School]] and [[Reigate College]] before studying media production and broadcast journalism at the [[University of Bedfordshire|University of Luton]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/article-rob-gale-named-first-coach-general-manager-of-valour-fc/|title=Rob Gale named first coach, general manager of Valour FC|last=Davidson|first=Neil|date=26 June 2018|work=The Globe And Mail|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref>

In 2000, Gale visited [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] for work and met his future wife Erin. After moving to Winnipeg permanently a year later, Gale and his partner married in 2003 and now have two daughters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/valour-fc-rob-gale-head-coach-1.4722467|title=Winnipeg's new soccer club names Rob Gale as head coach and GM|last=|first=|date=26 June 2018|work=CBC News|access-date=26 June 2018}}</ref> Five members of his family have [[UEFA]] coaching licences, including brother-in-law [[John Peacock (footballer)|John Peacock]].<ref name=":1" />

He is a lifelong [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] supporter.<ref name=":1" />

